\par\par \b \uc2  Govt warned it could lose int'l support. \b0\par\par\uc2 753 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 February 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesia risks losing support from foreign financial institutions if the country continues to neglect key reform strategies due to its lack of commitment and protracted political quarrels, economists said on Monday. \par \par \uc2  Noted economist Sri Mulyani Indrawati said foreign lenders were becoming impatient with the ineptitude shown by Indonesia in adhering to its own reform agenda as agreed to by the government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF). \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over Indonesia's commitment to reforms was hurting its relationships with foreign lenders, she said. "The question is whether Indonesia still wants to conform with international norms," Sri told reporters following an economics seminar relating to Syariah (Islamic law). \par \par \uc2  She was responding to recent comments made by President Abdurrahman Wahid's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  advisers, who urged Indonesia to mend ties with international institutions. \par \par \uc2  Relations between the IMF and the government have deteriorated since the Fund has showed no sign of disbursing its $400 million loan package originally due last December. \par \par \uc2  The IMF delayed the loan as the government failed to meet agreed reform agendas of divesting its stake in Bank Central Asia (BCA) and Bank Niaga. \par \par \uc2  Disagreement over decentralization issues and amendments to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law led the Fund to further prolong the delay in the third disbursement of its $5 billion bailout fund. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli added to the friction when he admitted before foreign journalists that the IMF was too demanding. \par \par \uc2  "Two months after delay, and still no review (from the IMF). It's not clear when the IMF is coming, and the international community is wondering what to make of Indonesia," Sri added. \par \par \uc2  She said a review by the IMF was vital to maintaining support from other international lenders, such as the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI). \par \par \uc2  "CGI and the Paris Club all refer to the condition that Indonesia must obtain the IMF's approval for the Letter of Intent (LoI)," she explained. \par \par \uc2  Economist Hadi Soesastro of the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) said Indonesia should have realized the importance of maintaining a good relationship with the IMF. \par \par \uc2  "We should be ashamed that foreigners have felt the need to come down here and remind us," Hadi said. \par \par \uc2  He said the LoI was signed by the government and as such it must be honored. \par \par \uc2  "Don't sign an agreement if you can't stick to it," he said. \par \par \uc2  If the government has problems with the IMF, he went on, it should resolve them internally instead of going \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Don't bring the problem into the open where it can become a political commodity," Hadi said in reference to Rizal's comments about the Fund. \par \par \uc2  Under the LoI, the government and the IMF set out key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs. Compliance to the LoI is a prerequisite for obtaining the IMF loans. \par \par \uc2  The IMF conducts regular reviews of the LoI's implementation prior to the disbursement of more loans. \par \par \uc2  But in the past two months, she continued, Indonesia seemed to have lost its motivation for reforms. \par \par \uc2  "I think to other countries this (\b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) would be very critical," Sri said. \par \par \uc2  She added that other suggestions by the foreign advisors were indeed only reminders to Indonesia of its reform commitments. \par \par \uc2  The advisors also urged the government to speed up financial reforms and to defuse political instability. \par \par \uc2  The President's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  advisors include former U.S Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker; Singapore's Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew; and former senior executive of Germany's \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  Ulrich Cartellieri. \par \par \uc2  "There is nothing new in their suggestions ... they are a reaffirmation of the very basic objectives the government must hold onto," she said. \par \par \uc2  Sri further commented that the government's move to amend the \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  Law 23/1999 had also caused concern among the international community. \par \par \uc2  "They (the international community) think the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become a political toy," she said. \par \par \uc2  Some analysts suspect that the amendment is merely a political maneuver to oust \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's current governor Sjahril Sabirin. \par \par \uc2  President Abdurrahman Wahid is known to dislike the governor, who was appointed to the position by former president Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Sri said foreign lenders were worried that the costly recapitalization of the banking sector would not stop the government from resorting to political intervention there too. \par \par \uc2  The recapitalization cost of over Rp 600 trillion (about US$63 billion) is causing a hefty \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  which the IMF's loans must fill. (bkm) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx2k003f5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscale