\par\par \b \uc2  WB warns of new crisis scenario. \b0\par\par\uc2 710 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 February 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The World Bank said on Friday Indonesia would likely "muddle through" and maintain macroeconomic stability, but warned there was also the significant possibility of a crisis. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank said Indonesia's fragile \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could collapse if the International Monetary Fund-sponsored \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program failed to be implemented, and if the political instability and social unrest in the country persisted. \par \par \uc2  "Unfortunately, there is also a significant possibility of a crisis scenario," the bank said in its latest report on Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "A breakdown in the government's extended arrangement with the IMF as a result of major \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slippage, including inadequate progress on bank and corporate restructuring, could lead to a rapid erosion of market confidence and deterioration in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions," it said. \par \par \uc2  "A similar outcome could result from political instability or a widespread deterioration in law and order. In such adverse situations, the bank would cease all new lending until base case conditions have been restored." \par \par \uc2  The World Bank said it would help prepare contingency plans in the event of another macroeconomic tumble in the country. \par \par \uc2  The warning came amid deteriorating relations between the government and the IMF, and continued unrest in the country, including a wave of ethnic clashes in Sampit, Central Kalimantan, which have thus far have left more than 140 people dead. \par \par \uc2  The IMF delayed in December the disbursement of its next US$400 million loan to Indonesia, because of concerns with the government-proposed bill on the amendment of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law, the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a delay in the privatization of Bank Central Asia (BCA) and Bank Niaga. \par \par \uc2  The release of the IMF money is seen as crucial to helping revive investor confidence in the ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  contracted by more than 13 percent in 1998 following the 1997 Asian financial crisis, and remained flat in 1999. But the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by about 4.8 percent last year, helped by strong exports and private consumption. \par \par \uc2  "Clearly, we have high expectations the government will be able to reach an agreement with the IMF ... because this is a precondition for restoring investor confidence," World Bank country director Mark Baird said. \par \par \uc2  In Washington, the International Monetary Fund said on Friday that talks with Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli were still continuing to resolve their differences. \par \par \uc2  Describing Wednesday's meeting between Rizal and IMF first deputy managing director Stanley Fischer as "productive", IMF spokesman Vasuki Shastri told The Jakarta Post by phone that "the two sides agreed to intensify discussion and remain in touch in the coming days." \par \par \uc2  Baird urged the government to speed up its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, particularly its corporate and bank restructuring programs. \par \par \uc2  "Many of the issues of concern to the IMF are also of concern to us," he said. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank report said Indonesia was striving to emerge from a severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, complete its transition to a democratic society and embark on an ambitious program of decentralization. \par \par \uc2  "Together, they constitute a highly complex agenda for Indonesia ... the stakes are high - not just for Indonesia but also for the international community," the report said. \par \par \uc2  The bank said the administration of President Abdurrahman Wahid inherited an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with deep structural flaws, weak institutions and an entrenched bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  "Corruption is still rampant and infects the very institutions (the police and judiciary) that are supposed to tackle it. \par \par \uc2  "Regional unrest and political and ethnic tensions threaten national unity and continue to preoccupy the government .... Investors remain wary of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the weak legal and judicial system and uneven \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  implementation," the bank said. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank launched on Friday its new loan package for Indonesia, totaling $400 million per annum over the next three years, compared to an average of $1.3 billion per year from 1990 to 1999. \par \par \uc2  The bank said about one-third of the new loan would be highly concessional credits from the International Development Association (IDA), which are repayable over 35 years, have no interest and come with a small administrative fee of 0.75 percent. \par \par \uc2  "The proposed amount ... will enable Indonesia to borrow money for poverty programs on much softer terms and avoid adding to its large external debt," it said. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx2o0047j\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Financial shares remain bearish throughout the week. \b0\par\par\uc2 245 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 February 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Jakarta: Financial s