\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah falls to lowest level in two years. \b0\par\par\uc2 620 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 February 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The rupiah dropped on Monday by 2 percent to its lowest level since October 1998 amid worsening ethnic violence in Central Kalimantan and problems with the International Monetary Fund. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah ended at Rp 9,830 per U.S. dollar late on Monday from Rp 9,685 on Friday, foreign exchange dealers said. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  senior deputy governor Anwar Nasution pledged that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would intervene in the market to help prevent the local unit from exceeding the Rp 10,000 level. \par \par \uc2  "We will continue to intervene in the market but we should also address the main problems, the unrest and political problems," Anwar was quoted as saying by Reuters. "Of course we hope we can stabilize the rupiah below 10,000." \par \par \uc2  Around 270 people have been killed in ethnic violence in Sampit, Central Kalimantan. The week-long violence has added jitters to a financial market already edgy by reports of worsening relations between Indonesia and the IMF. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said that the drop in the local currency was also driven by strong corporate demand on dollars to repay overseas debt. \par \par \uc2  Dow Jones news wires quoted dealers as saying that genuine corporate demand early in the day emerged around Rp 9,725 to Rp 9,775, prompting other participants to cover their short dollar positions. This triggered stop-loss dollar buying around Rp 9,800, which pushed the dollar to as high as Rp 9,865, they added. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah had dropped to as low as Rp 9,865 earlier on Monday, but found temporary respite when state banks sold dollars, probably on behalf of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and as commercial banks locked in profits, dealers said. \par \par \uc2  Dealers also said that the market was nervously awaiting for the result of last week's high-level talks between Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli and the IMF in Washington. \par \par \uc2  Relations between the government and the IMF had dropped to its lowest level after the Fund delayed the disbursement of its next US$400 million loan installment to Indonesia. The delay was made due to concerns over several issues including the government-proposed amendment to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law, a poorly-designed \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and delay in the sale of government ownership in Bank Central Asia and Bank Niaga. \par \par \uc2  The disbursement of the IMF money is seen as a key factor to help maintain investor confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and to open the way for other multilateral donors to provide their assistance to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Rizal said in a press conference late on Monday that the government and the IMF had reached an "agreement" over the difficult issue of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law amendment, paving the way for the Fund to proceed with the review of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program and the disbursement of its loan. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah had been relatively steady in the past month despite increasing political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  triggered by the legislature's censure of President Abdurrahman Wahid over alleged involvement in two financial scandals. The censure could lead to a process of impeachment. \par \par \uc2  The new foreign exchange ruling introduced by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the middle of January helped to maintain the stability of the local currency. \par \par \uc2  The new forex ruling basically bans rupiah transfers to nonresidents and cuts down the limit of forward transactions between onshore banks and nonresidents from Rp 5 million to Rp 3 million in a bid to help curb speculation against the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  But experts said that the restrictions had only served to slow down the rupiah's descent - and not halt it - as onshore dollar demand remains strong, and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political problems persisted. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx2r004m0\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
