\par\par \b \uc2  Bad news hits rupiah. \b0\par\par\uc2 772 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 February 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Indonesian rupiah remained at its new lows on Tuesday after falling 2 percent on Monday to almost Rp 9,890 against the U.S. dollar, already its lowest level since October 1998, suffering from an accumulation of bad news over the past ten days. Though the currency was up slightly amid significant dollar sales by state banks, it still hovered at over Rp 9,850, much weaker than the Rp 9,680 last Friday. \par \par \uc2  Without any positive factor, either in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  or political and security fields, market sentiment on the local unit will continue to be negative. The signal from the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  of an increase in its benchmark interest rate to defend the rupiah will not mean much in the absence of good news. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah had actually remained rather steady since mid-January, despite the censure of President Abdurrahman Wahid by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  in early February over his alleged involvement in two financial scandals. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  had consequently been able to curb further increases in its benchmark interest rate. \par \par \uc2  All this was made possible after the imposition in January of stricter foreign exchange regulations on offshore rupiah markets, which ban rupiah transfers to non-residents and impose a lower ceiling of US$3 million on cumulative forward deals that onshore banks may conduct with non-residents in the absence of underlying transactions. \par \par \uc2  But this gain has been nullified by the string of bad events affecting Indonesia over the past ten days, notably the worsening ties between the government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), grave warnings from Abdurrahman's international advisers, the gloomy report by the World Bank on the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook and renewed concern over the brutal ethnic clashes in Central Kalimantan that have so far killed more than 400 people. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli, who returned last weekend from a series of talks with IMF executives in Washington, failed to inject any new hope to remedy the murky situation. Though he did not explicitly acknowledge total failure of his talks in Washington, he did not have any significant progress to show off either. \par \par \uc2  Rizal could only claim that the government and the IMF had bridged their differences regarding the controversial amendments planned for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law and had agreed to form a panel of independent Indonesian and foreign experts to review the proposed amendments. All this still boils down to a likely protracted \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the IMF's bailout program for the country. \par \par \uc2  Little wonder then, that pressure on the rupiah since early this week did not come from the offshore market but from domestic demand, as more companies and investors moved to hedge their long rupiah positions before the dollar strengthens further. \par \par \uc2  Acknowledging that lingering political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems, and sporadic bouts of violence in Aceh and Maluku, had eaten away at the rupiah in the past year, wiping off some 25 percent of its value against the dollar, this new bout of depreciation will certainly portend a bleaker outlook of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Further depreciation of the rupiah will hurt the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , although oil revenues will rise in rupiah terms as foreign debt servicing and import costs increase as well. \par \par \uc2  A more devastating blow, however, would come from a rise in the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  which, a move suggested by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's Senior Deputy Governor Anwar Nasution on Monday. This is because most of the Rp 650 trillion in government bonds issued to bail out the banking industry are in the form of floating-rate bonds. The World Bank estimated last week that a one percent rise in the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate would mean additional costs of around $500 million (Rp 4.7 trillion) to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  However, because the pressure on the rupiah is swelling from a complex mix of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , political and security issues, a further increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not help much. Such a drastic monetary measure may even increase the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  woes as the weak banking industry will become more heavily burdened by negative spread, thereby eroding their capital base, and more loans may turn sour. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would therefore be well advised not to steeply raise its benchmark interest rate in the weekly auction of its promissory notes (SBI certificates) on Wednesday (today). \par \par \uc2  More market participants will continue to cover their short dollar positions, thereby putting stronger pressure on the rupiah, if President Abdurrahman, currently on his umpteenth travel overseas, does not immediately start leading the nation and seriously managing the government. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx2s004rf\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298