\par\par \b \uc2  Paris Club meeting likely to go ahead. \b0\par\par\uc2 495 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Minister of Finance Prijadi Praptosuhardjo said here on Wednesday that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the International Monetary Fund's (IMF's) review on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program would not affect the Paris Club meeting. \par \par \uc2  The minister said that he hoped the international creditors in the Paris Club would go ahead with their meeting in April. \par \par \uc2  According to the minister, the meeting which would discuss the Indonesian proposal to reschedule part of its sovereign debts is very important to lift the country out of the crisis. \par \par \uc2  The Paris Club agreed last year to reschedule Indonesia's sovereign debts worth $5.8 billion. \par \par \uc2  Analysts said that worsening relations between Indonesia and the IMF would have a great impact on the country's credibility in the eyes of the international community. \par \par \uc2  Without IMF backing, Indonesia will have trouble with its key donors - like the Paris Club of creditors and the Consultative Group for Indonesia - and confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would further erode. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian officials told reporters earlier this week that the fund will send a team on Thursday, but were unclear whether the visit would constitute an official mission. \par \par \uc2  The IMF, however, declined on Wednesday to confirm the visit. \par \par \uc2  "We have no comment or information on this report," Vasuki Shastry, a spokesman for the IMF, told Dow Jones. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the Fund's review would not only prolong the delay in its loan disbursement to Indonesia but also could affect the meeting of the Paris Club, which has regarded the Fund's review as an important gauge for its future debt facilities. \par \par \uc2  The IMF has delayed a $400 million tranche of its $5 billion loan to Indonesia since December amid concerns that the country is not moving fast enough on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia moved to patch up relations with the IMF last week by making progress on some missed \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform targets within its agreed program. \par \par \uc2  A major reason behind the delay of funds last year was the government's failure to sell PT Bank Central Asia and PT Bank Niaga, two nationalized institutions, by the deadline at the end of 2000. \par \par \uc2  The legislature, which had blocked the sales on grounds it would involve selling assets cheaply to foreigners, reversed its position last week. \par \par \uc2  The government also said last week that provincial governments could only borrow money after central government approval. \par \par \uc2  New laws which give power to the provinces over revenues and expenditures from this year have drawn criticism from the fund, which is concerned the regions could build up a huge debt, worsening Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position. \par \par \uc2  The IMF is also worried that plans to amend the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  law, making it easier for the government to fire the governor, could lead to political meddling in monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has said it plans to push ahead with the amendment, which could still form a major stumbling block with the fund, analysts say.(03) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx38003sz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
