\par\par \b \uc2  Faltering confidence. \b0\par\par\uc2 703 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The higher-than-expected 4.8 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth Indonesia posted in 2000 has apparently failed to increase market confidence or raise expectations of a stronger recovery. Instead, last year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  spurt, from zero growth in 1999 and a contraction of almost 14 percent at the peak of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in 1998, is expected to cool off this year as a result of external and internal factors. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank's latest report on Indonesia estimates \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year at 4 percent. This is a base-case scenario, assuming that macroeconomic stability is maintained and structural reforms implemented slowly, with frequent slippages and some \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reversals. The International Monetary Fund believes the best the country can expect is for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to remain flat. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has ventured a more optimistic projection of 4.5 percent to 5 percent expansion, but it used \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumptions that appear to be overly ambitious. \par \par \uc2  Most private sector analysts are less upbeat, estimating growth at between 3.5 percent and 4 percent. They cite fears that the country's political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue and export growth will slacken to 8 percent from 18 percent last year due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdowns in the United States and Japan, which together account for more than 32 percent of Indonesia's non-oil exports. \par \par \uc2  The optimists - foremost among them government economists - predictably contend \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion will become more robust as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities manage to disengage themselves from the political situation, as they did last year. \par \par \uc2  But key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data from the last few months has shown the ominous signs of a weakening pace of recovery. Despite the marked growth of 4.8 percent for the whole year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  actually shrank 0.7 percent in the fourth quarter of last year from the previous quarter. Non-oil exports, one of the three main engines of growth last year, fell 10.4 percent in January from December due to a harder-than-expected landing for the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Oil prices "boomed" in the first 10 months of last year before beginning to decline in the last quarter, and they are expected to continue their downward trend throughout this year. \par \par \uc2  The other two \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  engines - private consumption and investment - do not show great promise, either. This is the result of inimical domestic factors, notably the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the weakened leadership of the embattled President Abdurrahman Wahid, which have in turn affected the implementation of reform measures and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management as a whole. \par \par \uc2  Although the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to expect private consumption to rise by between 3 percent and 5 percent this year as a result of last year's estimated 16 percent increase in per capita income, that by itself will not be able to offset the decline in exports. \par \par \uc2  With rising political tension, a shrinking current account surplus due to faltering export growth, rising debt servicing commitments and a vulnerable rupiah, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  seems to have no other option but maintain a relatively tight monetary stance. \par \par \uc2  The problem, though, is that if the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  keeps its benchmark interest rate at almost 15 percent, where it has been over the last few months, many banks that were recapitalized with fixed-rate government bonds will continue to lose money, because they will have to offer deposit rates higher than the 12 percent returns on the bonds to remain competitive with other banks. \par \par \uc2  The third \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  engine - investment - has an even bleaker outlook, due mainly to the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the legal limbo regarding the huge pool of assets managed by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency and the shaky transition from centralization to regional autonomy. \par \par \uc2  All in all, the outlook is not comforting. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will most likely muddle through the multidimensional crisis in which the nation has been mired since 1998. It is hard to believe the optimists' view that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to grow robustly, isolated from the increased political turbulence. \par \par \uc2  Even if President Abdurrahman weathers the attacks of the emboldened opposition, he will emerge as a much weaker head of government who will have to make many compromises at the expense of prudent macroeconomic management. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx38003uj\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
