\par\par \b \uc2  Palangkaraya back to normal after violent incidents. \b0\par\par\uc2 513 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  PALANGKARAYA, Central Kalimantan (JP): The Central Kalimantan capital of Palangkaraya returned to normal on Sunday but tension was still in the air following a series of violent incidents on Thursday and clashes between indigenous Dayaks and police on Friday. \par \par \uc2  Army troops, rifles in hand, were standing by in strategic parts of the city and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  places, while police Mobile Brigade troopers guarded the Bunderan Besar area where Friday's violence took place. \par \par \uc2  The Army was actively involved in securing the city after the Central Kalimantan Police chief, Brig. Gen. Bambang Pranoto, officially requested military help in restoring order. \par \par \uc2  Some shops and markets were open and traffic was heavier than in previous days, but people said that the security outlook was still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Locals said that calm in the morning could easily turn into chaos in the evening. \par \par \uc2  Central Kalimantan Governor Asmawi Agani said to The Jakarta Post by phone on Sunday that he hoped that schools and commercial activities would be back to normal on Monday. \par \par \uc2  On Friday, Dayak demonstrators ran amok in the Bunderan Besar area in Palangkaraya in protest at the shooting of demonstrators on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  The protesters attacked several police stations and set a police truck ablaze, while hundreds of students also marched to the provincial legislature to protest the security forces' actions on the previous day. \par \par \uc2  Shortly after President Abdurrahman visited the riot-torn city on Thursday, Dayak residents took the streets demanding a resolution to the Sampit conflict, which has left at least 400 people dead. Most of the victims were Madurese migrants. The police opened fire to disperse the demonstrators and six people were reportedly killed. However, the police have so far only confirmed the death of Hendrison, 29, in the melee. \par \par \uc2  Central Kalimantan Police spokesman Second Adj. Insp. Andi Selvi told the Post on Sunday that the joint security measures introduced by the Police and the Army had proved to be successful. \par \par \uc2  Rumors have it that locals plan to stage an even bigger demonstration (than Friday's) on Monday. \par \par \uc2  "That could be just rumors," Andi said. "The most important thing is that the Police and the Army are ready to face any eventualities. But we hope that the worst doesn't come to the worst. Peace is much better for the people." \par \par \uc2  The provincial police chief Brig. Gen. Bambang Pranoto has issued a shoot-on-sight order against all rioters in a bid to restore law and order. \par \par \uc2  Governor Asmawi said he welcomed the decision. "I fully support it, but both the police and military must be wise in implementing the order so as not to enrage the people." \par \par \uc2  The governor also added that all cases related to the previous riots would be processed to the full extent of the law and "that means there will be no release of the 84 riot suspects." \par \par \uc2  "Sometimes we have to play by the book and sometimes we have to be flexible. This time we want security restored quickly and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," he added. (32/edt/sur) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx3c0044x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
