\par\par \b \uc2  Municipal bonds - A feasible strategy? \b0\par\par\uc2  By Achmad Mukhtar \par \uc2 644 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): When the laws on regional autonomy and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance were announced, two new catchwords become popular - autonomy and municipal bonds. What do they really mean, and are they workable in the domestic bonds market? \par \par \uc2  Income per capita has fallen sharply, unemployment has risen steadily, and political dilemmas loom - all this seems to contradict the promotion of municipal bonds, which has increasingly worried the International Monetary Fund. \par \par \uc2  There are a number of reasons why the issuance of municipal bonds needs much better preparation and time before being put into action. Firstly, our domestic financial market is declining. \par \par \uc2  The market for domestic bonds had not functioned well even prior to the crisis, and with a falling income per capita, bonds are unlikely to attract investors. Demand has declined significantly and the new issue of bonds has had to offer higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and implicitly higher risks too. \par \par \uc2  Consequently, domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rise, and when local governments issue their municipal bonds, known as munis in the market, there will be fierce competition in the bonds market among local governments, as well as between the government and the private sector. \par \par \uc2  As a result, there will be a crowding-out effect in domestic investment in the sense that some private companies cannot compete, and will delay or even cancel their planned investment. \par \par \uc2  Other factors that are worth considering include the fear of the impact of municipal bonds, alongside the unstoppable increase in the domestic minimum wage and poor domestic labor management, which has aggravated some companies in the manufacturing sector of shoes, toys and garments. They have now relocated factories to other countries such as Cambodia, Vietnam, or China. \par \par \uc2  In addition, the independence of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still a question mark among investors. "Independence" (kemandirian) could mean a "semi independent" \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  - a signal for higher inflation, for the simple reason that the central government has its own \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  constraints. \par \par \uc2  Given the government's tough burden in keeping to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and given a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , along with restricted sources of income from printing money and issuing new bonds, a non-independent \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  could easily finance the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  This is a real threat to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability as domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rise further, to keep the real interest rate acceptable to investors. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of rigid capital movement will only stimulate currency counterfeiting and substitution, diminishing hope for a full recovery. \par \par \uc2  A further reason is that if we look carefully at the laws on regional autonomy and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance, it seems there is no autonomy at the regional level except autonomy in issuing municipal bonds. \par \par \uc2  Local government autonomy means freedom for local governments to utilize their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources to maximize productivity through sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management. \par \par \uc2  When freedom to utilize \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources is still unclear, issuing municipal bonds becomes a boomerang for the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is not a self-fulfilling prophecy that we will have another \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political disaster, though it is likely to occur from a misconception in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Finally, foreign capital is still the prime engine of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether we like it or not, and most foreign investors are worried about the rule of law in this country. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to keep foreign investors away as any research will prove a waste of time, be it for direct investment in the real sector or a portfolio investment in the capital market. \par \par \uc2  As one struggling in the private sector, I really wonder what the government is doing to crank up the engine of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to get back on track to compete with the reviving economies of regional competitors, notably Thailand and South Korea. \par \par \uc2  It seems that we are wasting valuable time. \par \par \uc2  The writer is an investment strategist at Evergreen Capital, Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx3f0033m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
