\par\par \b \uc2  Revising gender-biased textbooks easier said than done. \b0\par\par\uc2 960 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following article by The Jakarta Post journalist Santi W.E. Soekanto looks at the issue of gender-biased school textbooks. Related reports and interviews written with contributors Herry Nurdi and Rani R. Moediarta are on Page 5. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Khofifah Indar Parawansa created quite a stir recently when she proposed that a number of elementary school textbooks be revised for containing "discriminatory" and "gender-biased" material. Acknowledging that her office of State Minister for the Empowerment of Women lacks the authority to undertake such a project, she nevertheless displayed her intent to push the relevant ministries to follow up her demands. \par \par \uc2  Quoting research conducted by scholars at the Jakarta State University, Khofifah cited how women and girls were only ever depicted in textbooks as kitchen dwellers. \par \par \uc2  Men and boys, on the other hand, were much less confined as they went to offices or played football. "That's discrimination against women," she said in a recent interview. \par \par \uc2  There have yet to be further reports about Khofifah's plan to invite the four publishers of the textbooks, including Erlangga and Pradnya Paramita, but her call for revision has led to more questions than answers. \par \par \uc2  Will the planned revision mean a withdrawal of the books? How and who will revise the texts? Who will say which materials are discriminatory, which are gender-fair? Who will finance the project? Should it be approved by the Ministry of National Education? \par \par \uc2  Will it, ultimately, further burden parents who have already been \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  a total of Rp 289 billion for textbooks annually? \par \par \uc2  Another important question is: how urgent is the motion to revise the textbooks? \par \par \uc2  Khofifah's concern is indeed justified, given how discrimination is still the lot of millions of Indonesian women and girls. But there are other, equally pressing matters to be handled. For instance, there is the crisis of schooling opportunities for Indonesian children. \par \par \uc2  A recent Unicef report said millions of Indonesian children are suffering from various clashes and protracted \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social crises. \par \par \uc2  At least 1.8 million children under the age of five (out of 23 million children in the same age bracket) are undernourished. Unless some massive, drastic measures are launched, Indonesian children will feel the impacts of the current crises in the next few years, Unicef said. \par \par \uc2  The report also pointed out that following the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  melt-down, the education \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  dropped by 40 percent. This means a decline in the quality of teaching because teachers have been forced to supplement their meager incomes with side jobs. \par \par \uc2  Do not forget, either, that over the past three years the number of school dropouts has also risen. \par \par \uc2  The second crisis hits Indonesian women and girls in particular - this is the onslaught of messages about women's self-esteem and about how they should behave. \par \par \uc2  The media and many people tell our girls that they are of value only if they are attractive - which often means not only skinny but anorexic - and pleasing to look at by men. \par \par \uc2  The girls, who spend hours glued to the television, are told through television dramas that women are to be chased by men and hit and discarded when they stand up for themselves. \par \par \uc2  The girls, too, are told that their bodies, their looks, sell all types of commodities from herbal concoctions to car batteries. They are brainwashed by commercials into believing that they are not worthy of anything unless they are fair-skinned and have dandruff-free hair. \par \par \uc2  They may achieve good marks in school but unless they have a flawless complexion that seduces men into touching their facial skin, they feel they are nothing. \par \par \uc2  Even in ordinary life, parents deliver the same message to their daughters. \par \par \uc2  It is not enough for them to do well in school or have good manners, they must look pretty. No wonder many girls who were confident and dared to take on the world in their childhood, grew up to be fearful women \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  of their worth and ability. \par \par \uc2  In many cases, these girls felt the impact of losing their self-esteem as soon as puberty began. They became unable to say no, because they did not think they were worthy of that option. \par \par \uc2  Physician Boyke Dian Nugraha pointed this out when he revealed that every year, 1.3 million teenagers have an abortion. \par \par \uc2  Mary Pipher, in her 1994 book Reviving Ophelia, says we live in a "look-obsessed, media saturated, girl-poisoning culture" that takes away a woman's self and imposes on her a fake-self. \par \par \uc2  "Despite the advances of feminism, escalating levels of sexism and violence - from undervalued intelligence to sexual harassment in elementary school - cause girls to stifle their creative spirit and natural impulses, which, ultimately destroys their self-esteem." \par \par \uc2  Though she writes mostly about American teenagers, her depictions seem eerily familiar for Indonesians. \par \par \uc2  "Many of the pressures girls have always faced are intensified in the 1990s. Many things contribute to this intensification: more divorced families, chemical addictions, casual sex and violence against women. Because of the media, girls all live in one big town - a sleazy, dangerous tinsel town with lots of liquor stores and few protected spaces," Pipher writes. \par \par \uc2  She adds, "Increasingly women have become sexualized and objectified, their bodies marketed to sell tractors and toothpaste. Soft-and hard-core pornography are everywhere. Sexual and physical assaults on girls are at an all-time high. Now girls are more vulnerable and fearful, more likely to have been traumatized and less free to roam alone." \par \par \uc2  This combination of old stresses and new is poison for our young women, she writes. \par \par \uc2  Even revising textbooks, it seems, will be a much easier task than taking on the challenges facing our daughters today. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx3j003eh\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
