\par\par \b \uc2  23rd March 2001, Editorials from Indonesia's Major Dailies. \b0\par\par\uc2 689 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 March 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  : ABDURRAHMAN'S AUSTRALIAN TRIP It is not often that one hears of President Abdurrahman Wahid altering his overseas travel itinerary in the face of criticism. His decision, therefore, to cut short his upcoming visit to Australia is something that Indonesians would do well to appreciate. There are ample grounds for the criticism. The country is in a mess. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook is bleak, with business slack and the national currency sinking further. Violence and civil strife continue to disrupt entire communities in Maluku and Kalimantan while in Irian Jaya and Aceh secessionists remain active. Abdurrahman Wahid himself is facing further censure and even possible impeachment by the national legislature. So, once again the President will leave the running of his troubled country to Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri and the Cabinet for six days. \par \par \uc2   But, important as Australia may be to Indonesia and much as this country needs Australia's support, most Indonesians seem to feel that, in times of erious trouble, a President should stay at home to look after the country and cope with any unanticipated emergencies. To the majority of Indonesians, the President's propensity to leave the country even while it is being swamped by adversity of every sort, makes it look as though the President has failed to comprehend the seriousness of the situation here. Ignoring this reality will certainly not help strengthen the President's hand in dealing with his adversaries at home. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  WILL WAR COME TO ACEH? There are now strong indications that the government is going to take military action against GAM - the Free Aceh Movement. TNI Commander Admiral Widodo said that several battalions of TNI troops will soon be dispatched to Aceh with the specific task of safeguarding the oil and gas plants in Arun, owned by American ExxonMobil and other industrial projects. Stung by a sudden attack against a helicopter which was taking off to take the Minister of Energy and Mining Resources to Lhokseumawe, Mahfud said that it is time to take actions against GAM, which he said had fired at the helicopter causing bullet holes in its fuselage. Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs took the viewpoint as Mahfud has expressed hat GAM is not interested in establishing peace in Aceh, and should therefore be forced to accept the peace proposed by the government in that territory. It was the closure of the Exxon plant which finally drove the TNI to beef up the strength of its troops because the government stands to lose considerable \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue if Exxon stops producing. For years, Exxon has been forced to slow down production due to the worsening security situation. So far GAM has avoided a full confrontational assault against the Arun plants, but has kept employees under mental pressure to remain home and stay away from the factory. Will war come to Aceh and cause the deaths of more people along with the destruction of towns and villages? Nobody will be able to answer this question. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  MILY OPERATION IN ACEH The helicopter which Mines and Energy Minister Purnomo Yusgiantoro boarded was shot in Aceh last Tuesday. The incident later prompted the government to become more determined to launch a military operation in the troubled province, albeit a limited one. The incident seems to be the peak of the government's annoyance with the Free Aceh Movement (GAM). The government said the separatist movement has destroyed the peaceful life and security in Aceh. More than that, Exxon Mobil, which mines natural gas in Aceh, which in turn is a main source of revenues for the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , has suspended its operation due to the absence of a security guarantee. The security in Aceh remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Exchanges of gunfire between armed rebels and government troops continue, disturbing the lives of the local people and the security of businesses. From this point of view, the limited military operation is an understandable measure to crack down on the separatists. Apart from that, the government in launching the military operation, must learn from the past. - Republika. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx3n001f1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
