\par\par \b \uc2  Editorials from major dailies 27/04/01. \b0\par\par\uc2 701 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 March 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  : DO NOT DESTROY DEMOCRACY The failure of our national leaders to break the political deadlock, confronting the nation in the past few months in response to President Abdurahman Wahid's reply to the first memorandum, will bring us nearer to the boiling point and imminent disaster, unless we are able to fund a solution acceptable to everyone in the days ahead. The most confusing in Indonesian politics is the fact that some rival national leaders such as President Wahid, Top Assembly Amien Rais and House Speaker Akbar Tanjung traded the same words. Both Rais and Tanjung condemned the method of intimidation, perpetuated by NU like brandishing the strength of its militant forces and suicide squads are means of open terror and intimidation. On the other hand, Wahid has maintained that "where we like it or not as the fourth president elected by the Parliament has the legality to remain in his current position until 2001 and it is in accordance to the country's constitution. \par \par \uc2   Hence, we prefer to give an advise to law enforcers not to underestimate the danger of situation and should therefore pay close attention to practices by certain elements which may seem to have no connection with the main body of suicide squads. Bleak condition often surrounds Indonesia's history particularly in the transfer of power as could be seen with resignation of the late Sukarno and former strongman Soeharto. We have warned Wahid not to involve himself in a risky game by using the muscle power of his youth branches in order to defend his position no matter how correct he is. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  LOOKING FOR STRATEGIC PARTNERS The government has prepared some measures to look for other sources of funds to be used as development funds. One of these is to focus on the privatization of 15 state companies by looking for strategic partners. Frankly speaking, it should be admitted that the situation at home would not attract both portfolio investors and strategic partners willing to put in capital in the country. The feeling of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has continued, prompting some foreign companies here to close down their activities. Privatization through strategic partners has been implemented in many countries and without meaningful obstacles. However in Indonesia, the issue on nationalism has still been raised, despite the fact that foreign companies have been allowed to own 100 percent of company shares. However, the issue on nationalism should prompt us not to accept quickly everything proposed by foreign investors, even though the country is going through a difficult stage. The Indonesians are facing a dilemma - its need for foreign investors on the one hand and placing nationalism on the track on the other. The government indeed is in a most difficult position. - Bisnis Indonesia \par \par \uc2  ENDLESS FIGHTS It is a most heart-pounding moment not only for Jakartans, but for all those concerned with the nation's fate. We are on the brink of a war as an independent country under a democratically elected president. This is the result of irrationalities stemming from power. President Abdurrahman Wahid recognized the supremacy of the law during his election, but has charged that the legal process toward his impeachment is unconstitutional. President Wahid has exerted all his energy to create the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion that his impeachment would be a violation of the law. Not only that, President Wahid also considers impeachment as "haram" and thus, he needs to be protected by the masses. We are in a deadlock because of arrogance. The conflicting parties must know that one of them will have to give in this situation. Unfortunately though, they are using the war chief, instead of the law, as the referee. The country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has lost its power, while the government has been paralyzed. The \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assembly which does not have the capacity to govern, has become the only engine running the state's life. Does it make any sense if we fight with all our energy only to find out who is right and who is wrong? Anywhere in the world, if a country is paralyzed, it is the government who should bear the responsibility and no one else. - Media Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx3r002g0\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
