\par\par \b \uc2  Power of capital in decentralization. \b0\par\par\uc2 871 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following is the second of two articles on cities undergoing decentralization by architect and urban expert Marco Kusumawijaya. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The fact that none of the intended superblocks were completed in Jakarta by the time the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis began, indicated that the developers' ambitions contradicted the system of a super-block itself. \par \par \uc2  Such a huge entity requires long-term sustainable stability that would ultimately be destroyed by the competition that it created, resulting in overheated speculation. \par \par \uc2  We have become only too familiar with a property business dominated by speculation and bad debts that has largely contributed to the wider \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Can this situation be improved? Maybe. But there are alternatives in the form of citizen movements that do not aim at changing the system, but at checking and correcting it. \par \par \uc2  This alternative harnesses the one unquestioned strength of decentralization, where the decision making process is brought closer to the stakeholders. The key term for this is "\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation", which is the prerequisite for continuously innovative and creative policies. \par \par \uc2  Popular participation is urgent for at least two reasons. The first is Indonesia's transitional condition - which needs to accommodate plurality and reduce the gap between members of the elite and the rest of society. \par \par \uc2  The second is the need to balance representative democracy which, across the world, is deemed insufficient for a fast changing world. \par \par \uc2  The sociologist Manuel Castells describes "urban movements" as "the processes of purposive social mobilization, organized in a given territory, oriented toward urban-related goals". \par \par \uc2  Observing historic moments in the late 1970s and early 1980s, he says that urban movements have become a critical source of resistance to the one-sided logic of capitalism, the predominant role of the state, and informationalism, or the dependency on information flow and power over information in governance and in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Urban movements in Europe, at that time, began to emerge from general discontent with the established lifestyle. \par \par \uc2  This was essentially because the failure of proactive movements - such as the labor movement and political parties - to counter \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  exploitation, cultural domination, and political oppression, had driven people to react on the basis of their respective localities. \par \par \uc2  There are three main sets of goals for urban movements to focus on: urban demands on living conditions and collective consumption; the affirmation of local cultural identity; and the conquest of local political autonomy and citizen participation. \par \par \uc2  In this context four main trajectories of the movements are synthesized: the integration of these movements into the structure and practice of local government; the nurturing of local communities as part of the environmental movement; the engagement of poor communities in collective survival offering reactive utopias - dreams which develop as a reaction to deep dissatisfaction, leading to resistance. \par \par \uc2  The first trajectory tends to strengthen local government, and will enhance inter-city competition. The fourth can become destructive if urban movements' appeals are not heard, if the new political avenues remain closed and if relatively new social movements such as feminism and new labor do not develop fully. \par \par \uc2  These are the conditions which we fear will come true with the increasingly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  development of the reform movement. \par \par \uc2  However, besides the problems posed by decentralization, villages to metropolises are also bursting from the inside. A high rate of urbanization has not been supported by a compatible urban culture. \par \par \uc2  The problem of Indonesian cities is not only in having to survive competition among each other, but also in developing themselves to at least reach minimum standards that are acceptable to their inhabitants and users. \par \par \uc2  Rapid urbanization has given little chance to develop urban order and a culture capable of dealing with contemporary conditions. Nowadays, Indonesians need to make the best use of the reform moment, to learn how to urbanize quickly, wisely and smartly. \par \par \uc2  We have the advantage of being latecomers. One thing that could make a difference is to widen the urbanization debate to include all segments in society. \par \par \uc2  The debate should also be enlarged to involve the arts, literature, architecture, and other cultural spheres besides the traditional technical and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework. \par \par \uc2  Awareness and conception about urbanization could be based on broad-based consensus. This is essential to reach a collectively acceptable concept and vision of urban civilization in Indonesia, whatever that may be. \par \par \uc2  An urban civilization needs to be developed proactively. Plans need to be drafted and carried out based on a clear "urban cultural strategy" for a better future, when most Indonesians will inhabit cities and the rest will use them intensely. \par \par \uc2  Participation and urban movements are ways to galvanize open-ended and rooted urban societies that can never be monopolized, reduced, or manipulated by any regime. \par \par \uc2  Social and cultural entities, through participation and urban movements will counterbalance top-down imposition of a homogeneous structure. \par \par \uc2  The urban kampongs must be strengthened, not only as housing areas to balance over-speculation of the property business, but also as enriching autonomous dwelling cultures to resist the powerful tendency of homogenization. \par \par \uc2  With healthy activism, even sporadic and small sized non-governmental organizations and civil society groups are very important, especially if they are able to develop an ever critical stance through sustained exchange of ideas and experiences. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx3s004ns\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
