\par\par \b \uc2  THURSDAY'S EDITORIALS IN MAJOR INDONESIAN DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,186 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 March 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  WHAT NEXT? President Abdurrahman Wahid was not far off the mark in concluding that his censure by the legislature, and the preceding investigation of corruption allegations against him, was nothing more than an attempt to oust him. The memorandum was issued on Feb. 1 on the basis of the House's investigation of the Buloggate and Bruneigate scandals, both of which implicated the President and his close aides. The fact that many legislators in the House had rejected the President's response before it was even delivered on Wednesday underscored their real motives. The President seemed to have missed - or chose to ignore-the real message that the memorandum had sent to him: That he no longer has the support of the majority in the House. The power struggle is far from over. The President has given his response and the House will have to decide on its reply in the coming days or weeks. \par \par \uc2   A second memorandum is a possible scenario if the House is consistent with its campaign to try to impeach the President. While there is a small chance that the President may win the battle, he will not likely win the war. Even if he survives the process, he will no longer be able to count on the support of the majority of the House factions. That being the case, his administration is likely to become even more ineffective than it is today. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  THE TEXTILE MAFIA Many foreign analysts acknowledge that the performance of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still fairly good despite the financial crisis that has descended upon the country since July 1997. It is unfortunate that the destruction of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was caused by weak government \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, which tended to put political considerations first in its making. Legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  or lack of a clean judiciary was another blow to the weakness. The export of textile and textile products are mentioned here as an example. The Forum of National Textile Businessmen (FPPN) revealed that the export value of Indonesia's textile and textile products has gone down 20 percent from the previous level. The forum said, the government did not have a clear cut \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the sharing of quotas which in turn hurt the textile businessmen. There is a strange thing that is happening in the field of Indonesia's textile industry: the presence of textile Mafia who regulate the quotas. In the New Order era, cooperatives grouped under the National Defense Force (TNI), were so powerful in determining the quotas. But once the soldiers withdrew from businesses as a show of reform within the TNI, so many more textile Mafioso are now emerging in more violent and cruel faces. Josephine Shaw, director of Hong Kong-based Global Asset Management has suggested to Asian businessmen, including Indonesians, to make some modifications in their corporate production strategies. Hopefully! - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  TOGETHERNESS FROM SENAYAN There was no "tumult" at the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assembly building where President Abdurrahman Wahid conveyed his reply to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) memorandum censuring him yesterday. Neither was there any "deviant" behavior from the president which sometimes irks legislators, as what had happened in the past. Only one legislator interrupted the president's speech at the end of the session, asking Wahid to calm down his supporters and tell them not to commit violent acts and vandalism. Outside the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assembly building, there was no mobilization of the masses, either those opposing or supporting President Wahid. This implied that rumors that pro-Wahid supporters would flock to Jakarta were totally unfounded. In fact, Jakarta was free from demonstration yesterday when the "political process" took place at the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assembly building in Senayan. It was a good sign. Indeed, we must learn how to exercise democracy in such a way that "political battles" must take place at the rooms already agreed upon instead of in the streets. Likewise, we must be aware that politics will give meaning to any event with interests and thus, as the adage suggests, there is no eternal buddy or rival in politics but there exist eternal interests. Once again, we would like to praise those who have managed to refrain from acts of destroying one another. We feel relieved to see what happened yesterday that there was awareness on the part of pro-and anti-Wahid supporters not to confront each other in the streets. This would undoubtedly serve as an asset to restore our togetherness which has been torn. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  THE NEED TO BE FAIR Aside from the people, the head of state had difficulty in getting others to observe his right to be treated fairly. At least, this was what was featured in President Abdurrahman Wahid's reply to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' first memorandum. The issuance of the memorandum, said the president, was not in accordance with the Constitution. He noted that he found it unfair because the House had issued the memorandum improperly. The president's reply to the memorandum (censuring him for his alleged involvement in Buloggate and Bruneigate) was read by Justice and Human Rights Minister Baharuddin Lopa at the House plenary session here Wednesday. The issuance of the House memorandum was the first to occur in Indonesian history. Promoting reconciliation among members of the political elite would be more beneficial than planning to issue a second memorandum, because the government is expected to be quick in acting to improve the situation in the country. - Bisnis Indonesia \par \par \uc2  PRESIDENT'S REPLY President Abdurrahman Wahid has replied to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) memorandum censuring him over two scandals known as Buloggate and Bruneigate. As widely expected, the president defended himself by declaring the memorandum illegal. He also tried to prevent the possibility of the House issuing a second memorandum. He argued that since he has replied to the first memorandum served to him early last month, a second memorandum is not worth issuing. On the donation from the sultan of Brunei, the president maintained that it was alms for the Acehnese people, presented to him in his capacity as an individual. Again, he defended himself regarding the announcement of the donation, which was managed by Haji Masnuh. The announcement was a must. However, it was certainly wrong for him to receive the money in his capacity as an individual without having to account for it to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Haji Masnuh is not a state official authorized to manage state funds, while the Aceh case is state affairs. Though an audit of the fund is possible, the mixing up of two different affairs might cause confusion. Thus, it is inevitable that we enact a law stipulating that any donation to a president and his relatives, in whatever form, with value exceeding a specified amount, must be presented to the government and become state property. Logically, it is impossible for the sultan of Brunei to present donations, including alms, to Wahid unless he is president. Thus, when it comes to donations, Wahid could not position himself as an individual because this would eventually lead to power abuse. - Republika. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx3t00151\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
