\par\par \b \uc2  Regions know what to do to develop themselves. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,201 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 March 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following is the first of two articles on management, written by Owen Podger, a management consultant who for the past year has been team leader for an ADB-grant technical assistance to support decentralization. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): This newspaper published on March 13 an article by Hans Vriens entitled "RI's chaotic decentralization", and I feel impelled to paint a considerably different picture. \par \par \uc2  Decentralization is indeed long overdue, and that many aspects of it are close to disastrous. But many of his statements just do not match with what I have seen across the country over the past year. \par \par \uc2  Vriens wrote that "municipalities have no clue how to govern". Yet bureaucratic leaders in regions have generally had more training in governing, Indonesian style, than civil servants in most countries. \par \par \uc2  There are certainly areas in which they have no experience, but in most new areas of responsibility most regions have inherited people who are quite capable, to a mundane level, to keep current processes of government running. \par \par \uc2  Concerning the areas where they have no experience, there are considerable risks to good government. Few regional administrations have any clue about regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development management, environmental management, land-use planning, or financial management - as distinct from book-keeping. \par \par \uc2  Over 70 percent of representatives in the almost four hundred local councils are new to their functions. Most of these people are searching for how to govern, but this is very different to saying they have no clue. \par \par \uc2  Vriens also says "nobody in Indonesia seems to know what to do with the more than two million central government civil servants who are based in the provinces". This is not true either. The vast majority of these civil servants are teachers, nurses and doctors, and they just continue to do what they were doing before, changing the sign on the door and asking for funding from a different source. \par \par \uc2  Regions do not know how to rationalize the bloated administrations they have inherited. They have inherited inefficiency, inappropriate appointments, overlapping functions, and many officers known to be corrupt or unsympathetic who, in the New Order, thrived in their higher status than the local administrators. \par \par \uc2  This means that regions do not yet know how to overcome the problems that already existed because of the centralist system. But at least they are now aware of the problem that the centralist system refused to see. Without doubt, there should be many redundancies, and the first to go would be those central government placements who have abused their central status and abused the citizens in the regions where they work. \par \par \uc2  Officials in land management, forestry and mines are particularly targeted by regional governments, often with very good reason. \par \par \uc2  Vriens says "nobody in Indonesia seems to know what are the responsibilities ... of the center, provinces and municipalities". This is a sweeping statement, hiding the positive aspects of how regions are coping, and the dangerous risks of duplicity. \par \par \uc2  The process of defining "authorities" of each level of government in legal terms has been an ongoing circus from the moment the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) passed the law on regional autonomy in May 1999, that is, for almost two years. \par \par \uc2  But in fact, most of the responsibilities of regions are clear in a managerial and operational sense, for the operations that were previously managed by the centre in the regions just keep on going on, under local administration. \par \par \uc2  Most of these operations are "business as usual", like running schools and hospitals. Approval of mining investment is not business as usual, and is therefore a matter facing greater difficulty. Improvement of the level of services and of efficiency is also not business as usual, and local amateur endeavours to make improvements are causing considerable trauma. \par \par \uc2  Changes in the organization of central departments in response to decentralization is not business as usual either, and almost every department shows signs of serious dysfunction. These are areas where there is very much chaos, but it is not the whole process by any means. \par \par \uc2  It would take years for mining to be properly managed in the regions, but where there are natural resources in the ground, regions will want to negotiate to get them out, not just for \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but more importantly for their economies. \par \par \uc2  They will start with pipe-dreams of how rich their governments will become, but they will negotiate to a reality, and they will go with mining executives to New York to expedite arrangements and to enter treaties. \par \par \uc2  In five years time, mining may not have returned to level it has been, but what is of more concern is that the mining sector, after a brief period of decline, may become the engine of reckless local development that destroys environment and again enslaves the workers. \par \par \uc2  The circus of defining authorities over the past two years is historically quite understandable. The New Order was notorious for its various classification systems of what government did, with sectors, programs and projects for the development \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , activities for the routine budge, and tasks and functions for its institutions. \par \par \uc2  The above law 22 1999 on regional autonomy attempted to introduce a new concept for classifying government, the concept of "authority". Authority was defined as the right to regulate and arrange, but the classification of authority was not defined in the law, except for mentioning a number of fields, that did not suggest an overall system of classification. \par \par \uc2  Instead of putting effort into how government "authority" should be classified, departments entered a drawn-out process of looking at what parts of what they did would not be siphoned off to the regions. To their merit, they did not make long lists of the things they would siphon off, leaving room for regions to consider their new authority. \par \par \uc2  Consideration of new authorities appropriately takes time, and will sadly leave wakes of confusion. The framers of the above law did not understand this, or allow for it. \par \par \uc2  The huge problem of preparing \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is mind-boggling. Last August, the People's Consultative Assembly, concerned at delays in completing \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  for autonomy, passed a decision that allows regions to make their own by-laws without waiting on the center, as long as they adjust their by-laws when the centre finally does prepare its regulations. \par \par \uc2  Few regions are likely to invest efforts to regulate without an indication from the center as to what the future \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may be, leaving uncertainly for all. \par \par \uc2  So now, the only way is to muddle through the legal process of defining authorities and determining procedures, and meanwhile keep on with the job of trying to assure that routine services, like health and education, do not collapse. \par \par \uc2  It is interesting to see that most regions have clear ideas (not necessarily commendable or legally defined) on most of what they are now to do, because it is not significantly different from what was being done before. \par \par \uc2  Again, the areas where the risks of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  are the highest are again the very same areas where the regions lack experience, in regional development, investment, land, mining, environment and financial management. The government must understand the degree of danger from these risks. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx3t0035b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
