par \par \uc2  NU SHOULD PRACTICE DEMOCRATIC PRINCIPLES When we reflect on statements issued by Nahdlatul Ulama (NU) clerics at their recent meetings in Rembang, Kediri and Sukabumi, we have reason to be weary of their intolerance and at the same time aggressive attitude against criticisms directed against NU leaders and President Abdurrahman Wahid. A recent statement by NU clerics in Sukabumi has been quite enervating because they act as if the NU is the personal fiefdom of Abdurrahman Wahid, who in their eyes can do no wrong. As NU former chairperson, Wahid became one of Indonesia's leading advocates for democratic reform and used the conservative and rural based areas of more than 30 million strong NU as a platform for asserting the democratic principles implied in Islam. In this instance we would like to express our appreciation at the negative response he gave to the opening of an office established by his fanatical supporters in Surabaya to recruit people to become members of a force to defend what Wahid called, "The Defender Front for Truth". We reject intimidation and fanaticism as a means to solve our political problems but should instead use reason, moderation and compromise to strengthen democracy in his country. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  POLITICAL FEVER BEFORE APRIL 30 With a view to lowering the political temperature in the runup to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) plenary session on April 30, President Abdurrahman Wahid is planning to hold a meeting with the three other national leaders, Megawati Soekarnoputri, Amien Rais and Akbar Tandjung. Although the meeting's agenda is still unclear, the president's plan shows he is seeking a way to reach a political compromise with his competitors before the House eventually issues a second memorandum of censure. What good would a meeting among the four national political figures be? President Wahid no doubt has an agenda. Indeed, in all honesty, there are many things they could discuss and compromise on. It is only proper for Wahid as head of state to take the initiative to achieve compromise and reconciliation, because apart from the DPR's plenary session he will also face the Paris Club meeting and the CGI (Consultative Group on Indonesia). If the four national political figures' meeting is just a cosmetic exercise, it might as well not take place because then even Wahid would not gain anything. In the meantime, the political process will run its course and we will eventually witness whether the government can withstand another shock. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx47001xz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
