\par\par \b \uc2  WEDNESDAY'S EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 817 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 April 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  HERE THEY COME The long-awaited review team from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) arrived here on Tuesday to conduct a two-week comprehensive evaluation of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, which were stipulated in the government's letter of intent (LoI) to the multilateral agency last September. The team's arrival itself, which had been delayed, since December, should be good news to the market, amid the escalating political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and weakening rupiah. Hopefully, with a new agreement with the IMF, the subsequently positive market sentiment toward the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be able to correct or at least reduce the deviations in the assumptions of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , thereby preventing an unmanageable explosive \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . However this potential gain could still be diluted if the bickering among the political elite and the hostility between President Abdurrahman Wahid and the House worsened. \par \par \uc2   The House's stance (to be made known on April 30) on Abdurrahman's recent response to its first memorandum of censure, will determine the effectiveness of a new LoI with the IMF in improving market confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If anything, whether the Abdurrahman government survives or is replaced this year, an IMF-endorsed, hence internationally-supervised reform package could still serve as an automatic pilot for the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management amid the political turbulence. - Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  GUS DUR'S WARRIORS At a time when the heated political controversy of the last several months is nearing its culminating point, we should consider it the responsibility of our national leaders to display a wise and serious attitude to prevent matters from getting out hand. We have heard alarming gossip that more than 30,000 loyalists of President Abdurrahman Wahid in East Java are set to stage an invasion of Jakarta, determined to carry out a Holy War against his political opponents. But a statement by Jakarta garrison commander, General Bibit Waluyo is considered off the mark when he extended a too cordial welcome to the Muslim militants. He said: "Please, let them come to Jakarta, but the most important thing is that they comply with existing regulations and orders. We have to realize that Jakarta is the nation's pride and joy and it belongs to all of us. Our Republic is based in Jakarta." We tend to forget, however that these warriors do not come to Jakarta to enjoy the sights or to take in the special filthy atmosphere of the capital but to cause chaos. They come here with the specific purpose to defend Wahid's position at whatever cost. A more business-like statement would have placed the situation in its rightful perspective. In the meantime we are expressing the hope that we will be able to escape forthcoming events unscathed. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  TALKS ON MEGAWATI'S CAPABILITY TO GOVERN AND LEAD ESCALATE Talks on political affairs in the country have made Indonesia's Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri become the focus of attention. \par \par \uc2  Being the vice president, assignments (to govern) would eventually fall on her lap if the political situation leads to the president's resignation or impeachment, through a decision of a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR). Even if the option of power-sharing is considered, with the president as the head of state and the vice president as the head of government, the duty to run the government would also fall on Megawati. It is thus logical for her to become the focus of attention when political crisis and stagnation in the government set in. What should be shown by Megawati is sincerity. Having a good intention, we believe that the solution to this should be sought together with Gus Dur (President Abdurrahman Wahid), within or without the constitutional process. - Kompas \par \par \uc2  JUDGING MEGAWATI'S THREE DEMANDS Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri does understand that experience is the best teacher. Thus, she floated three demands if people want her to become president, replacing incumbent Abdurrahman Wahid. To Megawati, these demands could become the most important reference in assessing the political elite. To us, there are at least three considerations in judging these demands - she needs full and sincere support from the political elite, she wants to build an elegant political tradition in a bid to create a win-win solution, and she needs a conducive climate to build Indonesia and help bail it out of the present multi-dimensional crisis. But could members of the political elite restrain themselves from making maneuvers when Megawati becomes president? Would they support her without bargaining? It seems difficult to answer these questions as politics is full of consensus and bargaining. That is the obstacle that we might face. In the presidential system, the power of a president as the head of state and head of government is difficult to be separated. If so, isn't the problem found in the 1945 Constitution? - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx4b0028z\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
