\par\par \b \uc2  Gus Dur, Mega discuss security. \b0\par\par\uc2 801 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 April 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Top state officials met here on Wednesday to discuss security ahead of the April 30 \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) plenary session, which will decide whether to issue the second memorandum of censure against President Abdurrahman Wahid. \par \par \uc2  The meeting took place as hundreds of members of the ready-to-die force in East Java were defying police orders to discontinue "war-training" to defend Abdurrahman, better known as Gus Dur. \par \par \uc2  "The meeting was to discuss the general security situation ahead of (the DPR plenary session) on April 30," presidential spokesman Wimar Witoelar said. \par \par \uc2  "The fact is there has been no violence (so far) and efforts will be taken to prevent any. No one has any interest in conflict." \par \par \uc2  Wimar was speaking after a luncheon at Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri's official residence in Central Jakarta, which was attended by the President, top military and police officials and key Cabinet ministers. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman's supporters are expected to stream into Jakarta on April 29 to join a mass prayer in support of the President. Police have also asked the event's organizers, Nahdlatul Ulama (NU), either to bring forward or delay the prayers for security concerns. \par \par \uc2  Police in Jakarta have begun weapons checks at entry points to the city in an attempt to prevent violence ahead of the crucial plenary session. \par \par \uc2  Those arriving at bus terminals, train stations, harbors and main roads would all be checked, a Jakarta police spokesman said earlier in the week. \par \par \uc2  Jakarta police chief Insp. Gen. Mulyono Sulaiman said on Wednesday that around 10,000 police personnel would be deployed to maintain security in the capital city on April 29. The number, he said, could be increased to 18,000 on April 30. \par \par \uc2  Fears that the President's supporters would also descend upon the DPR building on April 30 had prompted several legislators to call on the House leaders to relocate the plenary session outside the capital. \par \par \uc2  House speaker Akbar Tandjung flatly dismissed the suggestion on Wednesday, saying that the House plenary session "will stay in Jakarta". \par \par \uc2  "It did not even cross my mind to hold the plenary session outside the DPR building, let alone outside the capital," Akbar, who also chairs Golkar party, said. \par \par \uc2  He said that he had written a formal request for a security guarantee to the city police. \par \par \uc2  Yogyakarta Governor Hamengkubuwono X said earlier in the day that his city was ready to host the DPR plenary session, should House leaders decide to move it outside the capital. \par \par \uc2  The proposal to hold the plenary session outside Jakarta was first mooted on Tuesday by Arifin Panigoro, leader of Megawati's Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle faction at the DPR. \par \par \uc2  Speaking at the end of a two-day meeting between several legislators critical of Abdurrahman on the resort island of Bali, Arifin said the House plenary could be moved to the West Java capital of Bandung. \par \par \uc2  He then claimed that at least seven House factions had agreed to issue the second memorandum against Abdurrahman on April 30. \par \par \uc2  Akbar denied the suggestion, saying that no agreement had been reached between the House factions on whether or not to issue the second memorandum against the President. \par \par \uc2  He admitted, however, that the mood during the two-day talks in Bali was "moving toward that direction (of issuing the second memorandum)." \par \par \uc2  "There hasn't been any formal agreement, because the factions' final stance will be decided by their respective leaders," Akbar said. \par \par \uc2  He added that Golkar's final stand on the matter was being drafted by an 11-member team. The draft, he said, would be presented to the party's leaders on Monday. \par \par \uc2  If Abdurrahman's response to a second memorandum fails to appease the legislators, a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly could be convened by August to impeach him. \par \par \uc2  The House first rebuked the President on Feb. 1 over his alleged involvement in two financial scandals. In his response, Abdurrahman vowed stricter measures against corruption, including a proposal to reverse the burden of proof for suspects in corruption cases. \par \par \uc2  The United Development Party (PPP) legislator who attended the Bali meeting, Bachtiar Chamsyah, said on Wednesday that the informal talks also focused on how to build a clean and strong government. \par \par \uc2  "The country is in a state of emergency, particularly from the security point of view, due, among other things, to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship," said Bachtiar, who chaired the House special committee investigating the financial scandals that implicated the President. \par \par \uc2  He defended a plan to hand the President a second rebuke, saying that no improvement in the security and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fields had been made since the first memorandum had been issued. \par \par \uc2  He said Abdurrahman's government in fact lacked legitimacy because of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (byg) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx4j0050x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
