\par\par \b \uc2  Issue memorandum, but no impeachment, says Cabinet. \b0\par\par\uc2 490 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 April 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Cabinet on Saturday once again pleaded with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , warning them against going too far in its censure of President Abdurrahman Wahid. \par \par \uc2  Speaking at a media briefing after a Cabinet meeting, Cabinet Secretary Marsilam Simanjuntak and Minister of Justice and Human Rights Burhanuddin Lopa said despite issuing a second memorandum the House should not push further its censure. \par \par \uc2  "We hope the House will not ask for a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly because it will cause severe chaos among the people," said Lopa. \par \par \uc2  Lopa warned that the nation could be pushed to the brink of conflict, especially between supporters and opponents of the President. \par \par \uc2  The is the second time the Cabinet has conveyed a similar message in as many days. \par \par \uc2  On Friday Lopa made an unsuccessful plea to House leaders not to issue the second memorandum of censure against the President also citing fears of unrest. \par \par \uc2  The request is seen as a last ditch attempt before the House convenes on Monday to issue what is expected to be the second memorandum of censure. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for Social, Political and Security Affairs Gen. (ret.) Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono chaired Saturday's hastily convened Cabinet meeting. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman was not present as he was visiting East Java. \par \par \uc2  Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri was also absent following her purported bout of the flu. \par \par \uc2  "She is still sick and needs to rest," Vice Presidential Secretary Bambang Kesowo remarked. \par \par \uc2  There has been speculation that Megawati is politically distancing herself from the Cabinet, with her flu providing a convenient alibi for her absence at such a critical juncture. \par \par \uc2  During the briefing Lopa seemed annoyed by journalists who questioned whether Megawati supported the Cabinet's decision. \par \par \uc2  "If you don't trust me please ask her secretary (Bambang) who was also present in our meeting". \par \par \uc2  Marsilam said the results of the Cabinet meeting would be discussed with the President and Vice President, though he did not explain who would convey the message to Megawati. \par \par \uc2  Marsilam also hinted that the government would launch a massive campaign to oppose a possible special Assembly session which could impeach the President. However he did not elaborate further. \par \par \uc2  "What is also important is to conduct a wider popularization of the Cabinet's appeal not to continue the second memorandum, or that it does not need to be followed up by a special session to hold the President's accountable," said Marsilam. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Minister of Industry and Trade Lt. Gen. (ret.) Luhut Panjaitan said the supply of basic necessities had not been affected by the current political turmoil, claiming that stocks were sufficient for two months. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramli, however, warned that the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would collapse if the current \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  was not quickly resolved. \par \par \uc2  "We hope everyone will understand the seriousness of the situation," said Rizal after the Cabinet meeting. (prb) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx4t005b0\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
