\par\par \b \uc2  Streets, shopping centers deserted during mass prayer. \b0\par\par\uc2 646 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 April 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Most of the city's main streets were deserted and shopping centers quiet on Sunday as thousands of followers of the Nahdlatul Ulama (NU) Muslim organization conducted istighotsah (mass prayer) on Sunday. \par \par \uc2  The bustling downtown business district turned into a ghost town, with shops along Jl. Gajah Mada, Jl. Hayam Wuruk and shopping centers in Glodok area, West Jakarta closed amid fears of possible riots. \par \par \uc2  Only a few private cars traveled the streets while many \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation vehicles, such as buses and vans, carried no passengers. \par \par \uc2  The traffic was much clearer than it usually is on Sundays. \par \par \uc2  The city's main thoroughfares, such as Jl. Jend. Sudirman, Jl. MH. Thamrin, Jl. Gatot Subroto, all in Central Jakarta and Jl. Rasuna Said, Jl. MT. Haryono, Jl. Fatmawati and Pondok Indah area in South Jakarta were also quiet. \par \par \uc2  A bus driver complained of fewer passengers than usual. \par \par \uc2  He said the situation on Sunday reminded him of the Muslim holiday Idul Fitri. \par \par \uc2  "I should not have operated my bus but taken a rest at home," Suparjo, who drives a bus plying Bekasi-Blok M, was quoted by Antara as saying. \par \par \uc2  The shortage of buses forced people to wait for a long time. \par \par \uc2  A woman complained that she only found a bus from Tangerang to Kampung Melayu after almost an hour's wait. \par \par \uc2  "I just came out of Tangerang hospital after medical treatment. The politicians never think that their actions could cause us ordinary people to suffer," she said. \par \par \uc2  The bus, which usually took the city toll road, took a regular road when it reached Tomang junction due to the lack of congestion on the streets. \par \par \uc2  Slight tension marked the day as dozens of police officers were seen standing on alert at road junctions - which on a normal day are usually crowded - such as in Slipi, West Jakarta, Cawang, in East Jakarta and Lebak Bulus, South Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Some shops in Gajah Mada Plaza and in Glodok electronic market and nearby street traders defied the order of the day by staying open, although only a small number of visitors were seen. \par \par \uc2  "People were apparently afraid of possible riots so they were reluctant to go out, although we knew that it was just a prayer," one of the traders said. \par \par \uc2  A similar scene was visible in Pasar Pagi Mangga Dua, Lokasari shopping center and some entertainment spots in Mangga Besar, all in West Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Some shop owners said it would be business as usual on Monday, although they expected a low turn-out of visitors. The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  will decide on that day whether to issue a censure motion against President Abdurrahman Wahid for a second time. \par \par \uc2  Many NU followers decided to stay in the city longer to witness the result of the House's plenary session, defying their leaders' order to return home as soon as the mass prayer finished. \par \par \uc2  Besides shops owners who wished to keep their shops open on Monday, some taxi drivers promised that they would operate on that day. \par \par \uc2  "I don't care what will happen and I will just drive down the streets. Hopefully there will no chaos," one of the taxi drivers, Soeharto, said. \par \par \uc2  Quoting some media reports, he predicted the situation on Monday would remain calm. \par \par \uc2  He blamed the media for the quiet but tense atmosphere on Sunday and, perhaps on Monday, which he said had blown out of proportion the peaceful intention of the mass prayer. \par \par \uc2  "If I look at the television and newspapers, the situation here was distorted," he remarked. \par \par \uc2  He admitted, however, that political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  resulting from bickering among political leaders had contributed to the slump in the number of passengers and increase in prices of basic goods. \par \par \uc2  "I get bored with all the political news, now I only care about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  survival," he remarked. (jun) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010712dx4u0059w\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  President Wahid asked to be Accommodative. \b0\par\par\uc2 325 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 May 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  President Abdurrachman Wahid is asked to be \par \par \uc2  accommodative to others in the wake of the second memorandum of censure to \par \par \uc2  prevent further \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  deterioration, Hadi Soesastro, an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  observer from Centre for Strategic and International Studies said here \par \par \uc2  yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said Wahid's response to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR)'s second \par \par \uc2  memorandum of censure would affect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence. \par \par \uc2  "If the response was in confronting manner then \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be \par \par \uc2  deepening. But if the response was accommodating, the confidence would \par \par \uc2  grow," he said. \par \par \uc2  Hadi said within this one-month period Wahid is required to show good \par \par \uc2  performance, endorsing the parliament to respond with positive attitude \par \par \uc2  towards the government. \par \par \uc2  According to him, up to now Mr Wahid has several weaknesses, feeling as \par \par 