\par\par \b \uc2  WEDNESDAY 02/05/01 EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 763 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 May 2001\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Asia Pulse Pte Limited.< Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its\par \par \uc2  MUDDLING THROUGH \b \highlight22\uc2 UNCERTAINTY\b0 \highlight\uc2  The big question arising, now that the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has escalated to the probability of a change in government, is how the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will muddle through the transition period. How the government of President Abdurrahman Wahid will be able to manage the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid the sharply eroded market confidence and how reform measures can still proceed under a government whose credibility and popularity are now at their nadir. This is the kind of situation that urgently calls upon the President and the House, despite their differences, to demonstrate strong spirit of statesmanship by continuing good cooperation in leading the nation and country through the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is, therefore, most imperative that the President and the House immediately put their enmity aside and start setting deadlines for finalizing amendments to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws and consolidating a new reform agenda. \par \par \uc2   We cannot afford to waste any more time while the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to bleed. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  UNSATISFACTORY OUTCOME Parliament on Monday evening issued a second memorandum to President Abdurrahman Wahid granting him a one month respite to mend his ways and to improve the performance of his cabinet, and that failing this the House will move to call a special session of the MPR to impeach him. We have indeed succeeded in preserving a peaceful though hectic week preceding this event, but we are not too sure that its outcome will bring us nearer to an expected solution. We have every reason to doubt whether Wahid would be able to put the period of one month given him to good use to convince everyone that he is a changed person full of dedication to lead the cabinet to an improved performance. All in all we are not quite satisfied with the situation. On the one hand, there are distinct indications that legislators wish to spare the feelings of President Wahid, but in doing so they have delayed the solution of a problem which is going to cause lots of troubles. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  NATIONAL EDUCATION On Saturdays at about noon, avoid the areas of Lenteng Agung, Roxy, Kebayoran Baru, and Kramat Jati. Why? Because students often meet there for clashes. Saturday is their favorite day, \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  their free time fighting one another. Is this the result of education? It should not be. Today, May 2, is National Education Day. We should reflect on the state of the country's education - its curriculums and results. Another thing which needs some reflection is the quality of the country's education. However, whenever we talk about quality, we always end up asking - how can we improve education if its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation is only 3.83 percent or Rp 11.22 trillion of the Rp 295.1 trillion state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? That small allocation is even reduced through corruption. Once again, on this National Education Day, we really need to think much about the future of the country's education. Should we fail to make improvements, we can only become spectators in the midst of global competition. We will become an easy target of exploitation by \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  maniacs from other countries. - Republika \par \par \uc2  LABORERS AND EMPLOYERS The use of the word "laborer" was considered taboo during the 32-year New Order government. The word even disappeared for quite a long time for it was identified with communism, thus in its stead were used "worker" or "employee". Laborers were also in a bad bargaining position at that time that they hardly obtained protection. In this era of reform, the role of labor unions has strengthened. Labor unions and institutions for labor advocacy have emerged. They espouse the same principles, including the pursuit of justice and better working conditions for laborers. Labor action has also begun to escalate. In a positive way, this reflects a rise in the laborers' awareness of their rights. It forces employers to be careful in facing the aspirations of their employees. Employers can longer just do what they want to do with their workers - such as pay them poorly, ignore their rights, or lay them off. Moreover, the government is discussing the bill on labor unions, which is expected be advantageous to the labor sector. Employers and employees should always try to understand each other. Employers should not ignore their employees' aspirations that they will raise the latter's salaries only after they stage protests. Employees likewise have to be aware of their position. They should not abandon their jobs because of their stubbornness in demanding for their rights. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010709dx52001l7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
